questions.question:
Given below is a solution for the critical section problem of two processes P_i and P_j sharing the following variables:

var flag: array [0..1] of boolean; (initially false)
turn: 0..1;

The program below is for process P_i (i = 0 or 1) where process P_j (j = 1 or 0) being the other one.

repeat
  flag[i] := true;
  while turn != i do
  begin
    while flag[j] do skip;
    turn := i;
  end;
  critical section
  flag[i] := false;
until false

Determine if the above solution is correct. If it is incorrect, demonstrate with an example how it violates the conditions.

A. The solution is correct and satisfies mutual exclusion and progress
B. The solution violates mutual exclusion — both processes can enter the critical section simultaneously
C. The solution violates progress — if turn != i and flag[j] is false, P_i loops forever without entering the critical section
D. The solution violates bounded waiting — a process can be indefinitely postponed

Consider the following scheme for implementing a critical section in a situation with three processes P_1, P_2, and P_3:

repeat
  flag[i] := true;
  while flag[j] or flag[k] do
  begin
    if turn == j then
      flag[i] := false;
    while turn != i do skip;
    flag[i] := true;
  end;
  critical section
  flag[i] := false;
until false

(The program is for process P_i; P_j and P_k are the other two processes. turn is initially set to some process.)

a) Does the scheme ensure mutual exclusion in the critical section? Briefly explain.

A. Yes, mutual exclusion is guaranteed because each process checks flag[j] and flag[k] before entering
B. No, mutual exclusion can be violated when two processes simultaneously pass their respective flag checks
C. Yes, the turn variable ensures only one process enters at a time
D. No, the flag mechanism with three processes creates race conditions
